    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1953-07-28T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1953-07-28T00:00:00-05:00" n="605"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d605">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">Secretary’s Letters, lot 56 D 459, “M”</note>
                <head>No. 605<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">President <persName corresp="#p_EISENHOWER1" type="from"
                            >Eisenhower</persName> to Prime Minister <persName corresp="#p_LANIELJ1"
                            type="to">Laniel</persName>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d605fn1">Attached to this letter, along with <persName
                            corresp="#p_LANIELJ1">Laniel</persName>’s response of July 31 (<ref
                            target="#d607">Document 607</ref>), was a covering memorandum indicating
                        that this exchange of letters was being circulated for information to
                            <persName corresp="#p_MERCHANTLT1">Merchant</persName>,
                            <persName>Johnson</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_BONSALPW1"
                            >Bonsal</persName>, and <persName corresp="#p_MCBRIDERH1"
                            >McBride</persName>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1953-07-28">July 28,
                            1953</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Dear Mr. Prime Minister:</hi> I have asked <persName
                        corresp="#p_MACARTHURDII1">Douglas MacArthur, II</persName>, who, as you
                    know, is Counselor of the State Department, to proceed to Paris to convey to you
                    my warm personal greetings and to discuss with you informally problems of common
                    interest. One of these which is much on our mind these days is Indo China.<note
                        n="2" xml:id="d605fn2">A summary of the meeting between <persName
                            corresp="#p_LANIELJ1">Laniel</persName> and <persName
                            corresp="#p_MACARTHURDII1">MacArthur</persName>, which dealt with
                        matters relating to Indochina, was transmitted to the Department of State in
                        telegram 409, July 31; for the text of this telegram, see <ref
                            target="frus1952-54v13p1#pg_706">vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">xiii</hi>,
                            Part 1, p. 706</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <p>While I assume that Mr. <persName corresp="#p_MACARTHURDII1">MacArthur</persName>
                    will seek an audience with you in company with our Ambassador, if you should
                    want to give him any personal messages, I would be glad to receive them.</p>
                <p>You will recall that Mr. <persName corresp="#p_MACARTHURDII1"
                        >MacArthur</persName> brought us together in Paris some two years ago and I
                    hope that the acquaintance then begun can be renewed in the not too distant
                    future.</p>
                <pb facs="0274" n="1364" xml:id="pg_1364"/>
                <p>With assurances of my continued respect.</p>
                <p>Sincerely,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_EISENHOWER1">Dwight D. Eisenhower</persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
